``;``
. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> echo [[name size]; [ST 185] [KJ 160]]
â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # â”‚ name â”‚ size
â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 0 â”‚ ST   â”‚  185
 1 â”‚ KJ   â”‚  160
â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

```
To be a valid table, the number of columns needs to line up.
’گگعOTitle: title: Nushell 0.19
Path: Table literals (sophiajt)
Content:
Starting with 0.19, you can now write table values like you would other kinds of values. To do so, separate a row of header names from the data using a 
``;``
. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> echo [[name size]; [ST 185] [KJ 160]]
â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # â”‚ name â”‚ size
â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 0 â”‚ ST   â”‚  185
 1 â”‚ KJ   â”‚  160
â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

```
To be a valid table, the number of columns needs to line up.
—ظVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2020-09-01-nushell_0_19.mdظ@d2220deefa51b335ed924cd543281dfa7b413873f7a35e9fcc7ef28ae9cf027b³title: Nushell 0.19‘؛Multiline edits (sophiajt)ع®In addition to the new table literals, we're opening up multiline commands. Initially, this will be for the line editor, but we'll extend this further as we improve parser support.
You can now also write the above:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> echo [
[name, size];
[ST, 185]
[KJ, 160]
]
â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # â”‚ name â”‚ size
â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 0 â”‚ ST   â”‚  185
 1 â”‚ KJ   â”‚  160
â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

```
You might have noticed we now also allow commas to separate cells. These are intended to help readability and give a more familiar syntax for people coming from other languages.
’گگعَTitle: title: Nushell 0.19
Path: Multiline edits (sophiajt)
Content:
In addition to the new table literals, we're opening up multiline commands. Initially, this will be for the line editor, but we'll extend this further as we improve parser support.
You can now also write the above:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> echo [
[name, size];
[ST, 185]
[KJ, 160]
]
â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 # â”‚ name â”‚ size
â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
 0 â”‚ ST   â”‚  185
 1 â”‚ KJ   â”‚  160
â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

```
You might have noticed we now also allow commas to separate cells. These are intended to help readability and give a more familiar syntax for people coming from other languages.
—ظVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2020-09-01-nushell_0_19.mdظ@0e507e3c5f661c79ac9f9941916f36d773b87ef9d0ab10e09860793a3f59cd3a³title: Nushell 0.19‘ظ/Nushell celebrates its first year in the publicعWe recently sat down and wrote about 
[link: http://www.nushell.sh/blog/2020/08/23/year_of_nushell.html] where Nushell has come over the last year
 and some thoughts about where it's going. The blog post is a wealth of information about Nu's philosophy and direction. Well worth a read.
